<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-061-378  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 061 378.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 15 1990 v24 n3 p93(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The rewards of being ready: a few preparations before hiring aconsultant can save your firm money.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ruhl, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies can save substantial amounts on billing fees by taking afew simple steps before a consultant arrives.andP;  A fully functionalwork environment should be set up, including a microcomputer withthe company's standard software already installed, proper securityauthorizations and storage space.andP;  The programming environmentshould be explained clearly, including manual locations, correctuse of project libraries and company coding standards.andP;  Atechnically competent employee should be available to answer theconsultant's questions.andP;  Most importantly, have a clear idea ofwhy the consultant is being hired.andP;  Consultants say that companieswaste the most money in hiring consultants for ill-defined tasks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ConsultantsPersonnel ManagementProductivityGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>